16/03/2005
ANKARA, Turkey -- Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdogan met with his Macedonian counterpart, Vlado Buckovski, on Tuesday (15 March) to discuss boosting bilateral co-operation. They confirmed plans to improve collaboration in the defence sector and on issues related to EU and NATO integration. A bilateral agreement on economic co-operation was also sealed.
In other news Tuesday, Turkey's Parliament again adopted a controversial law that grants amnesty to students expelled from universities, including women dismissed for wearing traditional headscarves in class. The legislature re-endorsed the law, which was vetoed by President Ahmet Necdet Sezer earlier this month. 
Also Tuesday, Turkey and the IMF agreed on extending their current loan deal through 2007. The present $18 billion agreement expired in February. Ankara would get an additional $10 billion in loans between 2005 and 2007 while agreeing to control inflation and introduce additional market reforms. (NTV - 16/03/05; BBC, Macedonian government Web site, Makfax, A1 TV, AFP - 15/03/05)
